commit.message:
Add GFM-style superscripts and subscripts.

This is an extensive change that defaults to using GFM style
superscripts, i.e. a^b^ instead of just a^b or a^(b).  This is the
default form for pandoc as well.  This form can be overridden by the new
LOWDOWN_SUPER_SHORT flag and corresponding --parse-super-short option.

While here, allow for subscripts as well.  Subscript syntax overlaps
with ~~strike-thrus~~, which are enabled by default; however,
strike-thrus start with two tildes, while subscripts use only one.

commit.message:
Implement pandoc-style superscripts.

Prior to this, superscripts followed the traditional Markdown syntax
(which is also MMD).  Most users, however, use pandoc, which is pretty
bad in comparison: it has convoluted white-space rules and doesn't allow
nested superscripts.

Since these are incompatible, switch to using the pandoc-style ones by
default, and add an option for using the traditional "short" ones.
